-- U.S.-based stock funds attract $2 bln over week - Lipper
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Thu May 29, 2014 05:37PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, May 29 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds committed $2 billion to stock funds in the week ended May 28 after pulling $7.6 billion out of the funds the prior week, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Stock mutual funds attracted $388 million in new cash, while stock exchange-traded funds attracted $1.6 billion. Stock mutual funds are commonly purchased by retail investors, while stock ETFs are thought to represent the institutional investor.  Taxable bond funds attracted $2.9 billion in new cash, marking their 12th straight week of inflows. Funds that specialize in emerging market bonds attracted $331.5 million, marking their third straight week of inflows.